      "SummaryText": "EPA RISK MANAGEMENT PLAN\n\nEXECUTIVE SUMMARY\n\nTYSON FOODS    BUFFALO, NY\n\n\n1.  Accidental Release Prevention and Emergency Response Polices:\n     To insure safe operation and release prevention at Tyson Foods BUFFALO, NY, this facility has implemented The Occupational Safety and Health Administration's Chemical Process Safety Management Program 29 CFR 1910.119.  All operators of systems containing the threshold amount of hazardous chemicals will undergo Chemical Process Safety Management training and operator training specific to the system.\n\nTo insure proper response to emergency situations, Tyson Foods BUFFALO, NY., has implemented Emergency Action Plans as required by Occupational Safety and Health Administration 29 CFR 1910.38(a) and Emergency Response Plan 29 CFR 1910.120.  All safety personnel and operators of the process will be trained in these emergency procedures.\n\n2.  Stationary Source and Regulated Substances Handled:\n     At Tyson Foods' BUFFALO, NY facility Anhydrous Ammonia is used as a refrigerant in a closed loop system.\n       \n3.  General Accidental Release Prevention Program:\n     This facility complies with the Occupational Safety and Health Administration's Chemical Process Safety Management 29 CFR 1910.119 and the Environmental Protection AgencyA?s Risk Management Program 40 CFR Part 68.  \nFor ammonia systems Tyson Foods, Inc. has adopted the International Institute of Ammonia Refrigeration guidelines for system operation and maintenance.  Tyson Foods Inc. uses the IIAR Basic Ammonia Refrigeration Training Series for all operators.  \n \n4.  Five-year Accident History:\n     We had one accidental release resulting in one injury requiring a hospital visit for observation on 10/28/2008; the team member was not admitted to the hospital.\n                 \n5.  Emergency Response Program:\n     A fully trained and equipped Emergency Response Team is avaliable.  This team is trained to the Hazardous Materials Responder-Technician response capability in ac"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 1,
      "FacilityID": 1000021432,
      "SummaryText": "cordance with OSHA 29 CFR 1910.120 (q).  The team is capable of affecting all control measures (both confinement operations and containment operations) required to remediate the incident.\n\nA written Emergency Response Plan has been developed and is on record at the Facility.  This plan includes Pre-Emergency Planning with Outside Agencies (Buffalo Fire Department), Personnel Roles and Lines of Incident Command Authority, Facility Hazard Analysis and Emergency Prevention, Safe Distances and Places of Refuge, Site Security and Control, Evacuation Routes and Procedures, Decontamination Procedures, provisions for Emergency Medical Treatment, Emergency Notification Procedures, Chemical Response Procedures and Post Incident Response Critique.\n\nAll Tyson team members are taught in Hazard Communication to report any observed chemical leaks/spills and odors to their supervisor or lead person immediately.  Supervisors are taught to report the above to the Safety or Maintenance department immediately for further investigation.  Actions requiring a Hazmat team will be by Mollenberg-Betz/National Vacuum HAZMAT responders and if necessary, the Buffalo NYFD will also assist with in the response.  MSDS information books are accessible to all Tyson team members and outside HAMAT Responders for review.\n     \n6.  Planned Changes to Improve Safety:\n     Continued Inspection of equipment and replacement thereof as needed.\n\n7.  Process Safety Information is updated for each Tyson Foods' project that is not a Like-In-Kind replacement; PSI is due and was updated prior to performing the PHA for Evaporator Installation project."
